Photo: Henry Fisher Refreshment Saloon and California Candy Factory and Fancy Cake Bakery, 118 J St. in Sacramento c.1869 In the historical narrative of California's past, we find it divided into two distinct regions during the era of Spanish colonial rule, which lasted for several centuries. These regions were known as Baja California and Alta California, each holding its significance within the larger framework of New Spain, which later became Mexico. Baja California, the southern part, encompassed the Baja Peninsula and extended roughly up to modern-day San Diego, California. Beyond this point, Alta California began, stretching northward. The eastern and northern boundaries of Alta California remained rather vague during this time. Despite limited physical presence and settlements, the Spanish asserted their claims over a vast expanse that now constitutes the western United States. In the year 1821, Mexico achieved its independence from Spanish colonial rule. Initially, it emerged as the First Mexican Empire and later transformed into the Mexican Republic. In this context, Alta California transitioned from a province to a territory, with Monterey, California, as its territorial capital and a governor holding executive authority. The period following Mexico's independence from Spain was marked by political instability, characterized by approximately 40 changes in government for 27 years, with each government having a relatively short tenure of about 7.9 months on average. Tensions between the United States and Mexico escalated due to disputes over territorial boundaries, particularly involving the Republic of Texas. Matters worsened when Texas was annexed by the United States in 1845. A series of conflicts between U.S. and Mexican forces eventually led the United States Congress to declare war against Mexico on May 13, 1846, marking the commencement of the Mexican-American War. News of this conflict reached Alta California approximately a month later. The U.S. Navy received orders to assume control of all California ports in preparation for war. The Pacific Squadron deployed around 400 to 500 U.S. Marines and Navy sailors, poised for potential land actions. On August 13, 1846, a combined force consisting of U.S. Marines, Navy sailors, and elements of Fr√©mont's California Battalion, transported by the USS Cyane, entered and took control of Pueblo de Los Angeles. In September 1846, Mexico organized a campaign to resist the American incursion into Los Angeles from the previous month. Consequently, the outnumbered U.S. troops temporarily evacuated the city but recaptured it in early January 1847. After 1847, California was governed (albeit with considerable difficulty due to desertions) by a U.S. Army-appointed military governor, supported by a relatively small force of just over 600 troops. By 1850, California's population had swelled to over 100,000, thanks to the influx of non-Indian and non-Californio (Spanish and Mexican settler) residents drawn by the California Gold Rush. As part of the Compromise of 1850, Congress passed the California Statehood Act on September 9, 1850, granting California official statehood status. The California Gold Rush attracted individuals from diverse countries, backgrounds, social classes, and races, with the majority being young men. Women, although few, found unique opportunities to engage in various activities and assume new roles. These adventurers, often called Argonauts, embarked on journeys to California, either by traversing the California Trail or arriving by sea. In 1849 alone, around 80,000 Argonauts made their way to California, with approximately 40,000 traveling overland and the remainder coming by sea. The need for essential supplies in the goldfields drove the development of transportation networks. Large freight wagons, drawn by teams of up to 10 mules, facilitated the delivery of crucial provisions such as firewood, lumber, food, equipment, clothing, mail, and packages to the miners. The demand for meat, particularly beef, soared during this period, causing cattle prices to surge from $1.00 to $2.00 per hide to an astounding $30.00-$50.00 per cow. The dawn of California's railroad era commenced in February 1855 with the construction of the first railway line connecting Sacramento to Folsom, California. This 22-mile (35 km) line aimed to capitalize on the prosperous gold mining activities in Placerville, California, although its completion coincided with the decline of mining in that area in February 1856. Between 1860 and 1903, a succession of railroad mergers and acquisitions reshaped California's transportation landscape. These developments culminated in the emergence of four major interstate railroads that served the state: the Southern Pacific Railroad, Union Pacific Railroad, Santa Fe Railroad, and Western Pacific Railroad. Each railroad controlled one (and in the case of Southern Pacific, two) of the transcontinental railways that linked (truncated)

‚ÄúMajesty Surfacing‚Äù / Brown bears are generally solitary creatures, but when fall comes, and the salmon return to the Yukon's rivers, these nomads are forced to crowd into close proximity. Each one has their preferred fishing technique: some are divers, some pounce, others charge up the middle of the river, and some wait stealthily on rocks. In the case of Morris the bear, his preferred method was to ‚Äúsnorkel‚Äù with his face submerged in the river and his ears free to detect potential threats. Tensions can run high as the bears all vie for the best fishing spots. Keeping an ear out for any unruly neighbors while pursuing salmon is a clever way to avoid conflict. Wooden Leg: A Warrior Who Fought Custer is a 1931 book by Thomas Bailey Marquis about the life of a Northern Cheyenne Indian, Wooden Leg, who fought in several historic battles between United States forces and the Plains Indians, including the Battle of the Little Bighorn, where he faced the troops of George Armstrong Custer. The book is of great value to historians, not only for its eyewitness accounts of battles, but also for its detailed description of the way of life of 19th-century Plains Indians. The book was dictated to Marquis by Wooden Leg in Plains Indian Sign Language, their only common language. Marquis gathered the stories for the book from Wooden Leg and others while he was physician at the agency in Montana from 1922. They were reluctant to open up to him at first, but eventually Marquis gained their trust. Wooden Leg lived through some of the most turbulent times in Cheyenne history, but the book begins with his childhood and descriptions of Cheyenne customs. These include tribal organisation, the warrior societies, sport, religion and mythology, their friendship and cooperation with the Sioux, arrow recognition, warbonnet entitlement, and much more. Wooden Leg was introduced to warfare at a very young age via conflict with the Crow and joined the Elk warrior society at age 14. The book describes Wooden Leg's participation in the important battles of the war of 1876‚Äì1877, when the Cheyenne, Sioux, and other plains tribes fought the United States. These included not only the Little Big Horn, but the preceding Battle of the Rosebud and the succeeding Dull Knife Fight. Following the Cheyenne surrender, the tribe was deported to Oklahoma, but eventually Wooden Leg was allowed to return. At Fort Keogh he worked as a scout for the army and was later appointed a judge at the Tongue River Indian Reservation. Wooden Leg describes in detail how he befriended the old chief Little Wolf towards the end of the latter's life. Little Wolf had been a great war leader but was now ostracised for having killed another Cheyenne while drunk. Wooden Leg's description of the Battle of the Little Bighorn caused controversy when the book was first published, particularly his claim that many of the US soldiers committed suicide. This claim is still discussed by scholars and has been investigated by archeologists, but no firm conclusions have been reached.

Belvelly Castle Cobh Co.Cork üè∞. Belvelly Castle was built by the Anglo Norman Hodnett family in the 12th century. During the reign of Henry III, the Hodnett and de Barry families were in conflict over properties in the Cork area. In 1329 the fued between the families continued resulting in de Barry family and their allies- the Roches- besieging and capturing Belvelly Castle renaming it Barrymore. In 1581, Sir Walter Raleigh gained ownership of the Castle, the Raleigh coat-of-arms can be seen over the front door entrance at ground floor level. In 1636 , Sir Peter Courthope, an MP for Cork, rented the Castle for 15 years, adding a new roof and battlements. On this date in 1973, CHER began a two week run at No.1 on the US singles chart with HALF-BREED, her second US No.1 (Oct 8, 1973) "My father married a pure Cherokee My mother's people were ashamed of me The Indians said I was white by law The White Man always called me "Indian Squaw"" In her second chart-topping hit (after "Gypsys, Tramps & Thieves"), Cher sings from the perspective of a mixed-race woman who grew up as an outcast because she was a "half-breed." Because she was only part Caucasian and part Native American, she wasn't accepted by either race and found herself looking for validation in dead-end relationships with men. Cher was born Cherilyn Sarkisian in El Centro, California, to an Armenian American father and an Arkansas-born mother with English, German, Irish, French, and Dutch ancestry. Around the time "Half-Breed" was released, Cher claimed she was also 1/16th Cherokee on her mother's side. Snuff Garrett produced the song despite his intention to quit working with Sonny and Cher. He had been battling Sonny, the singer's then-husband, over what type of material she should be singing. Lyricist Mary Dean wasn't aware of the conflict when she brought "Half-Breed" to Garrett, a song she wrote with Al Capps specifically for Cher. Garrett recalled in a 1973 Rolling Stone interview: "I said from the lyrics it's a smash for Cher and for nobody else... And I didn't even have Cher at the time. To me, nobody else could do that song but Cher - that was Cher's story. So I held the song and then it worked out that we got Cher back, but the song sat in my desk for about three, four months." Cher is backed my session musicians from LA's famous Wrecking Crew, including Hal Blaine on drums. By the time this hit #1, Sonny & Cher's recording career as a duo had hit the skids with their last single, "Mama Was A Rock and Roll Singer," petering out at #77. Their marriage wasn't performing much better; they divorced in 1975. The music video aired as part of The Sonny & Cher Comedy Hour. Cher is decked out in a sexy Native American-themed costume, including a feathered headdress, and sings the tune from atop a horse.

De beelden zijn vreselijk... Als reactie op de aanval die Hamas gisteren vanuit Gaza lanceerde, ontketent het Isra√´lische leger een zoveelste keer zijn vuurkracht. Maar laten we duidelijk zijn: de oorlog die Benjamin Netanyahu en zijn regering vandaag zeggen uit te roepen tegen de Palestijnen, is al meer dan 75 jaar geleden begonnen. Aan de basis van het probleem liggen de Isra√´lische apartheid en bezetting, het onrecht en het dagelijkse geweld dat al die tijd al straffeloos wordt gepleegd. ‚ÄúDe onwettelijkheden worden in de eerste plaats gepleegd door Isra√´l, dat al 16 jaar een militaire blokkade in stand houdt, wat volgens het internationaal recht gelijk staat aan agressie. Meer in het algemeen is er de bezetting van de Palestijnse gebieden, met een kolonisatie die alleen maar toeneemt, met een hele reeks repressieve maatregelen tegen de Palestijnse bevolking, waaronder de vernieling van huizen‚Äù, legde Fran√ßois Dubuisson, professor internationaal recht aan de ULB, gisteren terecht uit op de RTBF. De toestand verslechtert nog met de huidige Isra√´lische regering, die bestaat uit extreemrechtse krachten. Dat toonden de gebeurtenissen van het voorbije jaar duidelijk aan: de invallen in de heilige plaatsen van de Al-Aqsa-moskee, de toenemende kolonisatie, met name van Sheikh Jarrah (Oost-Jeruzalem), de 247 Palestijnse doden sinds het begin van het jaar (v√≥√≥r dit weekend), de moord op journaliste Shireen Abu Akleh, de herhaalde aanvallen van Isra√´lische kolonisten op het dorp Huwara en de aanval op het vluchtelingenkamp van Jenin. Op 28 augustus publiceerde de ngo Human Rights Watch een alarmerend rapport waarin die het recordaantal Palestijnse kinderen die straffeloos worden gedood door de Isra√´lische bezettingstroepen, scherp veroordeelt. De Isra√´lische premier Benjamin Netanyahu verklaart nu: ‚ÄúWe gaan Gaza in een woestijn veranderen. Ik zeg tegen alle inwoners van Gaza dat ze moeten vluchten.‚Äù Maar waar moeten ze heen als ze al 16 jaar opgesloten zitten in een openluchtgevangenis van maar een paar vierkante kilometer? Niemand kan de situatie begrijpen of een oplossing voorstellen zonder deze realiteit in acht te nemen. Ook de steun van de Verenigde Staten en van Europese landen aan Isra√´l vormt een deel van het probleem. In plaats van Netanyahu te steunen in zijn oorlog, moeten we oproepen tot een onmiddellijk staakt-het-vuren en een dringende de-escalatie. Zeker omdat het conflict zich dreigt uit te breiden over de hele regio. Er moet een uitweg komen aan deze tragische spiraal van geweld: de bezetting be√´indigen is de enige manier om tot een rechtvaardige en duurzame vrede te komen.

text: By now, you are all aware of the recent devastating escalation in the Israeli-Palestinian ‚Äòconflict‚Äô. Fingers are being pointed and statements of solidarity are being shared by various governments and individuals. I also have something to say. First, as a doctor, I absolutely despise any senseless loss of life to violence and war. Wars do not determine who is ‚Äòright‚Äô. They determine who is left. But we cannot, and must not, be blind when it comes to understanding how this situation has arisen. The events of the past 24hrs have been framed as an ‚Äòunprovoked‚Äô attack. But this is not factual. It‚Äôs fuelled by the continued occupation of Palestinian land, deemed illegal under international law, and declaring part of that land as your capital city. It‚Äôs fuelled by the continued settler expansion, deemed illegal under the Fourth Geneva Convention. It‚Äôs fuelled by the desecration of Muslim and Christian holy sites during their holiest of celebrations. It‚Äôs fuelled by the military checkpoints that humiliate and subjugate. It‚Äôs fuelled by forced removals from homes and property, which is then handed over to the occupiers to inhabit. It‚Äôs fuelled by ‚Äòincursions‚Äô into sovereign Palestinian territory to arbitrarily arrest young men and minor children, and by convictions obtained by forced confessions under torture. It‚Äôs fuelled by the assassination of journalists like Shireen Abu Akleh, and then the harassment of her mourners at her funeral cort√®ge. It‚Äôs fuelled by an unjust legal system that consistently rules in favour of the occupying entity and imprisons, dispossesses and punishes Palestinians. It‚Äôs fuelled by an occupier that has literally imprisoned two million people in an open air refugee camp and controls how much water, electricity and aid can enter their territory. It‚Äôs fuelled by an apartheid system that treats Palestinians as second class citizens. It‚Äôs fuelled by a government that engages in provocative actions like filling in the water wells of Palestinians and evicting them from their homes. If you think that what you are seeing today is ‚Äòunprovoked‚Äô then you haven‚Äôt been watching what has been happening to Palestinians for the past 70 years. If the above isn‚Äôt the definition of provocation, then what is? All life is sacred. Human and animal. Muslim, Christian and Jew. Palestinian and Israeli. But I‚Äôm not willing to ignore all the factors at play which have lead to this critical point and pretend that Israel hasn‚Äôt breached dozens of UN Resolutions. I‚Äôm not willing to pretend that its current occupation of Palestinian Territories isn‚Äôt illegal under international law. I have no doubt that this war will escalate and a lot of innocent people will suffer. As usual, it‚Äôs women and children who will bear the brunt of this escalation. That‚Äôs why we, as the international community, need to demand that our governments do more than just offer platitudes, and that they actually work to bring about lasting peace through a two-state solution, the right of return, and recognition of East Jerusalem as the capital of Palestine. Anything else is just lip service and hypocrisy. - Sara Photo caption: the funeral cort√®ge of Palestinian Aljazeera journalist Shireen Abu Akleh, murdered by Israeli snipers, harrassed by the same murderous forces who killed her. NATIVE AMERICANS ‚Äì THE FIRST OWNERS OF AMERICA Native Americans, or the indigenous peoples of the Americas, are the pre-Columbian inhabitants of North and South America and their descendants. Those who live within the boundaries of the present-day United States are composed of numerous, distinct tribes, bands and ethnic groups, many of which survive as intact, sovereign nations. Most authorities agree that the first evidence of people inhabiting North America indicates that they migrated here from Eurasia over 13,000 years ago, most likely crossing along the Bering Land Bridge, which was in existence during the Ice Age. However, some historians believe that people had migrated into the Americas much earlier, up to 40,000 years ago. These early Paleo-Indians spread throughout the Americas, diversifying into many hundreds of culturally distinct nations and tribes. Application of the term ‚ÄúIndian‚Äù originated with Christopher Columbus, who, in his search for Asia, thought that he had arrived in the East Indies. However, there is considerable evidence in support of successful explorations which led to Norse settlement of Greenland, the L‚ÄôAnse aux Meadows settlement in Newfoundland, and potentially others some 500 years prior to Columbus landing in the Bahamas. From the Native American aspect, many tribes‚Äô oral histories indicate they have been living here since their genesis, as described by a wide range of creation myths. By the time European adventurers arrived in the 15th century, scholars estimate that more than 50 million people were already living in the Americas. Of these, some 10 million lived in the region that would later become the United States. As time passed, these migrants and their descendants pushed south and east, adapting as they went. With these new arrivals came centuries of conflict and adjustment between Old and New World societies. Today, Native Americans account for about 1.5 percent of the United States population, many of whom continue to take pride in their ancestral traditions ‚Äî still practicing the music, art, and ceremonies that took place many years ago. As far as I know Fatah still want a two state solution on 1967 borders and that seems only way forward to me. And the fact that Fatah have not called on their militants to join the uprising suggests to me that even now there is a chance for negotiation to bring this nightmare to a swift end. But it must end with justice for the Palestinians. It‚Äôs a tragedy of history that Hamas was originally tolerated - and some say funded - to split the secular-socialist Palestinian movement as part of the wider Western ‚Äòanticommunist‚Äô strategy of the late Eighties. ‚ÄúForgiveness‚Äù Once upon a time, in a hidden glen deep within an ancient forest, there lived a faerie named Abbie. Abbie was unlike the other faeries; she possessed a unique power that had been a mystery to her for as long as she could remember. She had the ability to forgive. In the faerie realm, forgiveness was a rare and powerful gift. Most faeries held onto grudges and slights, cherishing them like prized possessions. But not Abbie. She had a heart full of compassion and understanding, and she believed in the power of forgiveness to heal even the deepest wounds. One day, a great dispute erupted in the faerie community. It started as a simple argument between two families over the ownership of a magnificent crystal that was said to grant its possessor immense power. As the dispute escalated, it threatened to tear the entire glen apart. Abbie watched in dismay as her fellow faeries grew more and more consumed by anger and bitterness. She knew she had to do something to bring peace to her beloved home. With her gentle demeanor and kind heart, she approached the leaders of both families and offered to help mediate their conflict. At first, the feuding faeries were skeptical. They had never heard of forgiveness as a means of resolving disputes. But Abbie spoke to them about the healing power of letting go of anger and resentment. She shared stories of how forgiveness had transformed the lives of humans in the world beyond the forest. Slowly, the faeries began to listen. Abbie‚Äôs words touched their hearts, and they started to see the wisdom in her approach. She encouraged them to open their hearts to forgiveness, to release the burdens of anger and hatred they had been carrying for so long. It wasn‚Äôt an easy journey, but Abbie was there every step of the way, offering support and guidance. Over time, the feuding faeries began to forgive each other, and a remarkable transformation took place. The crystal, once a symbol of power and division, lost its luster and faded into obscurity. As the glen filled with the harmonious laughter of faeries who had once been bitter enemies, Abbie realized the true power of forgiveness. It wasn‚Äôt just about ending conflicts; it was about healing hearts, restoring relationships, and bringing about a profound sense of peace. Abbie‚Äôs unique gift had not only saved her home but had also shown her fellow faeries the incredible strength that lay in forgiveness. From that day forward, Abbie became known as the faerie of forgiveness, and her wisdom was sought by all who wished to mend their broken bonds. In the heart of the ancient forest, a lesson had been learned, and the power of forgiveness continued to shine as a beacon of hope and love, lighting the way for faeries and creatures of all kinds to find their own path to reconciliation and peace.

"The Omen" is a 1976 supernatural horror film directed by Richard Donner and written by David Seltzer. An international co-production of the United Kingdom and the United States, it stars Gregory Peck, Lee Remick, David Warner, Harvey Spencer Stephens, Billie Whitelaw, Patrick Troughton, Martin Benson, and Leo McKern. The film's plot follows Damien Thorn, a young child replaced at birth by his father, unbeknownst to his wife, after their biological child dies shortly after birth. As a series of mysterious events and violent deaths occur around the family and Damien enters childhood, they come to learn he is in fact the prophesied Antichrist. The Omen. Directed by Richard Donner Written by David Seltzer Produced by Harvey Bernhard Starring: Gregory Peck Lee Remick David Warner Billie Whitelaw Cinematography Gilbert Taylor Edited by Stuart Baird Music by Jerry Goldsmith Production company Mace Neufeld Productions Distributed by 20th Century Fox Release dates June 6, 1976 (UK) June 25, 1976 (US) Running time: 111 minutes Countries: United Kingdom, United States Language English Budget $2.8 million Box office $60.9 million (United States and Canada) Released theatrically by 20th Century Fox in June 1976, The Omen received mixed reviews from critics but was a commercial success, grossing over $60 million at the U.S. box office and becoming one of the highest-grossing films of 1976. The film earned two Oscar nominations, winning Best Original Score for Jerry Goldsmith, his only Oscar win. A scene from the film appeared at number 16 on Bravo's 100 Scariest Movie Moments. The film spawned a franchise, starting with Damien: Omen II, released two years later, followed by a third installment, Omen III: The Final Conflict, in 1981, and Omen IV: The Awakening in 1991. A remake was released in 2006.

De beelden zijn vreselijk... Als reactie op de aanval die Hamas gisteren vanuit Gaza lanceerde, ontketent het Isra√´lische leger een zoveelste keer zijn vuurkracht. De regio staat eens te meer in lichterlaaie en voor de komende uren en dagen moet het ergste worden gevreesd. Onze gedachten gaan uit naar alle onschuldige burgerslachtoffers, aan beide kanten. 

Maar laten we duidelijk zijn: de oorlog die Benjamin Netanyahu en zijn regering vandaag zeggen uit te roepen tegen de Palestijnen, is al meer dan 75 jaar geleden begonnen. Aan de basis van het probleem liggen de Isra√´lische apartheid en bezetting, het onrecht en het dagelijkse geweld dat al die tijd al straffeloos wordt gepleegd.

‚ÄúDe onwettelijkheden worden in de eerste plaats gepleegd door Isra√´l, dat al 16 jaar een militaire blokkade in stand houdt, wat volgens het internationaal recht gelijk staat aan agressie. Meer in het algemeen is er de bezetting van de Palestijnse gebieden, met een kolonisatie die alleen maar toeneemt, met een hele reeks repressieve maatregelen tegen de Palestijnse bevolking, waaronder de vernieling van huizen‚Äù, legde Fran√ßois Dubuisson, professor internationaal recht aan de ULB, gisteren terecht uit op de RTBF. 

De toestand verslechtert nog met de huidige Isra√´lische regering, die bestaat uit extreemrechtse krachten. Dat toonden de gebeurtenissen van het voorbije jaar duidelijk aan: de invallen in de heilige plaatsen van de Al-Aqsa-moskee, de toenemende kolonisatie, met name van Sheikh Jarrah (Oost-Jeruzalem), de 247 Palestijnse doden sinds het begin van het jaar (v√≥√≥r dit weekend), de moord op journaliste Shireen Abu Akleh, de herhaalde aanvallen van Isra√´lische kolonisten op het dorp Huwara en de aanval op het vluchtelingenkamp van Jenin. Op 28 augustus publiceerde de ngo Human Rights Watch een alarmerend rapport waarin die het recordaantal Palestijnse kinderen die straffeloos worden gedood door de Isra√´lische bezettingstroepen, scherp veroordeelt. 

De Isra√´lische premier Benjamin Netanyahu verklaart nu: ‚ÄúWe gaan Gaza in een woestijn veranderen. Ik zeg tegen alle inwoners van Gaza dat ze moeten vluchten.‚Äù Maar waar moeten ze heen als ze al 16 jaar opgesloten zitten in een openluchtgevangenis van maar een paar vierkante kilometer? 

Niemand kan de situatie begrijpen of een oplossing voorstellen zonder deze realiteit in acht te nemen. Ook de steun van de Verenigde Staten en van Europese landen aan Isra√´l vormt een deel van het probleem. 

In plaats van Netanyahu te steunen in zijn oorlog, moeten we oproepen tot een onmiddellijk staakt-het-vuren en een dringende de-escalatie. Zeker omdat het conflict zich dreigt uit te breiden over de hele regio.

Er moet een uitweg komen aan deze tragische spiraal van geweld: de bezetting be√´indigen is de enige manier om tot een rechtvaardige en duurzame vrede te komen.

NATIVE AMERICANS ‚Äì THE FIRST OWNERS OF AMERICA Native Americans, or the indigenous peoples of the Americas, are the pre-Columbian inhabitants of North and South America and their descendants. Those who live within the boundaries of the present-day United States are composed of numerous, distinct tribes, bands and ethnic groups, many of which survive as intact, sovereign nations. Most authorities agree that the first evidence of people inhabiting North America indicates that they migrated here from Eurasia over 13,000 years ago, most likely crossing along the Bering Land Bridge, which was in existence during the Ice Age. However, some historians believe that people had migrated into the Americas much earlier, up to 40,000 years ago. These early Paleo-Indians spread throughout the Americas, diversifying into many hundreds of culturally distinct nations and tribes. Application of the term ‚ÄúIndian‚Äù originated with Christopher Columbus, who, in his search for Asia, thought that he had arrived in the East Indies. However, there is considerable evidence in support of successful explorations which led to Norse settlement of Greenland, the L‚ÄôAnse aux Meadows settlement in Newfoundland, and potentially others some 500 years prior to Columbus landing in the Bahamas. From the Native American aspect, many tribes‚Äô oral histories indicate they have been living here since their genesis, as described by a wide range of creation myths. By the time European adventurers arrived in the 15th century, scholars estimate that more than 50 million people were already living in the Americas. Of these, some 10 million lived in the region that would later become the United States. As time passed, these migrants and their descendants pushed south and east, adapting as they went. With these new arrivals came centuries of conflict and adjustment between Old and New World societies. Today, Native Americans account for about 1.5 percent of the United States population, many of whom continue to take pride in their ancestral traditions ‚Äî still practicing the music, art, and ceremonies that took place many years ago. Who Gets To Be 'Hapa'? ‚ÄúHapa means part Native Hawaiian ‚Äî not part Asian‚Äù ‚ÄîPiikea Kalakau, middle school teacher "There are times when it feels like identity theft" ‚ÄîKealalokahi Losch, a professor of Hawaiian studies & Pacific Island studies at Kapi'olani Community College Sunset in Waikiki: Tourists sipping mai tais crowded the beachside hotel bar. When the server spotted my friend and me, he seemed to relax. "Ah," he said, smiling. "Two hapa girls." He asked if we were from Hawaii. We weren't. We both have lived in Honolulu ‚Äî my friend lives there now ‚Äî but hail from California. It didn't matter. In that moment, he recognized our mixed racial backgrounds and used "hapa" like a secret handshake, suggesting we were aligned with him: insiders and not tourists. Like many multiracial Asian-Americans, I identify as hapa, a Hawaiian word for "part" that has spread beyond the islands to describe anyone who's part Asian or Pacific Islander. When I first learned the term in college, wearing it felt thrilling in a tempered way, like trying on a beautiful gown I couldn't afford. Hapa seemed like the identity of lucky mixed-race people far away, people who'd grown up in Hawaii as the norm, without "Chink" taunts, mangled name pronunciations, or questions about what they were. Over time, as more and more people called me hapa, I let myself embrace the word. It's a term that explains who I am and connects me to others in an instant. It's a term that creates a sense of community around similar life experiences and questions of identity. It's what my fianc√© and I call ourselves, and how we think of the children we might have: second-generation hapas. But as the term grows in popularity, so does debate over how it should be used. Some people argue that hapa is a slur and should be retired. "[It] is an ugly term born of racist closed-mindedness much like 'half-breed' or 'mulatto,'" design consultant Warren Wake wrote to Code Switch after reading my piece on a "hapa Bachelorette." Several scholars told me it's a misconception that hapa has derogatory roots. The word entered the Hawaiian language in the early 1800s, with the arrival of Christian missionaries who instituted a Hawaiian alphabet and developed curriculum for schools. Hapa is a transliteration of the English word "half," but quickly came to mean "part," combining with numbers to make fractions. (For example, hapalua is half. Hapaha is one-fourth.) Hapa haole ‚Äî part foreigner ‚Äî came to mean a mix of Hawaiian and other, whether describing a mixed-race person, a fusion song, a bilingual Bible, or pidgin language itself. This original use was not negative, said Kealalokahi Losch, a professor of Hawaiian studies and Pacific Island studies at Kapi'olani Community College. "The reason [hapa] feels good is because it's always felt good," he told me. Losch has been one of the few to study the earliest recorded uses of the term, buried in Hawaiian-language newspapers, and found no evidence that it began as derogatory. Because the Hawaiian kingdom was more concerned with genealogy than race, he explained, if you could trace your lineage to a Hawaiian ancestor, you were Hawaiian. Mixed Hawaiian did not mean less Hawaiian. Any use of hapa as a slur originated with outsiders, Losch said. That includes New England missionaries, Asian plantation workers and the U.S. government, which instituted blood quantum laws to limit eligibility for Hawaiian homestead lands. On the continental U.S., some members of Japanese-American communities employed hapa to make those who were mixed "feel like they were not really, truly Japanese or Japanese-American," ‚ÄîDuncan Williams, a professor of religion and East Asian languages and cultures at the University of Southern California He said this history may have led some to believe the word is offensive. For Losch, "hapa haole" ‚Äî meaning part Hawaiian, part other ‚Äî always has been positive. "This is absolutely who I am," he said. The license plate on his car reads, "HAPA H." His family members have been proud hapa haole for generations. An issue for him is when non-Hawaiians call themselves hapa. "There are times when it feels like identity theft," he said. This is arguably the trickier and more significant conflict around the term. Hapa, middle school teacher Piikea Kalakau told me, means part Native Hawaiian ‚Äî not part Asian. "I ... am personally frustrated with the world misusing this word ...," she wrote in an email. I followed up with Kalakau by phone. The widespread use of hapa, she said, is a form of cultural appropriation, just as offensive as hula dancer dolls shaking their hips on car dashboards. She said correcting the definition of hapa is part of a larger Native Hawaiian "movement to take back our culture." She said her people were fighting to thrive again after surviving colonization and its damage to their language, culture and population. Kalakau encouraged me and other mixed Asian-Americans to find labels from our own (truncated)

Social disintegration is one of the core themes in the novel# Things Fall Apart by Chinua Achebe. It rises in the last chapters of the book where Umofia, an Igbo tribe is threatened by white domination. This brings pain to the reader who was perhaps sympathizing with the traditions and culture of the people of Umofia. The image of African native community and culture is presented in ' Things Fall Apart' by Achebe is an image of a coherent social structure. The white men are self-proud, cunning and aggressive and they have a plan to envangelize the tribes, where as the tribesman are humble naive. The white men have destroyed the Umofia by separating it's men to fight and blame each other, tying their tails to fight each other like dogs. Achebe explores that the whole of the cultural encounter, conflict and final disintegration of the tribe: " The white man is clever. He came quietly and peacefully with his religion. We were amused at his foolishness and allowed him to stay. He has put a knife on the things that held us together and we have fallen apart". Cultural beliefs and religion have a long history of playing a vital role in uniting people to a one voice. It is therefore difficult to unite a community with different cultures and religious beliefs. Though it is a clear misconception that the African culture is savage and primitive, it is however a mistake also to expect every other culture to develop and grow on the Western model. The African culture never need a redeemer like the white man's. #Things Fall Apart By Chinua Achebe #ChinuaAchebe #IgboProverb #AfricanLiterature #TellOurStory

GOVERNMENT OF FIJI REAFFIRMS COMMITMENT TO THE SAFETY AND WELL-BEING OF FIJIAN CITIZENS IN JERUSALEM Suva, Fiji ‚Äì In light of the recent escalation of conflict in Israel and the Gaza Strip, the Government of Fiji wishes to provide an update to the people of Fiji regarding the safety and well-being of the 200 Fijians who are currently in Israel to observe the Feast of the Tabernacle. The situation in the region has become increasingly volatile, with the Israeli army issuing evacuation orders to residents in several areas of the Gaza Strip in anticipation of retaliatory strikes against Hamas. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's commitment to "mighty vengeance" following what he referred to as a "black day" further underscores the gravity of the situation. Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka expressed his condolences, saying, "We are deeply saddened by the loss of lives and the suffering endured by both Israelis and Palestinians as a result of the ongoing conflict. Our thoughts and prayers go out to all those affected during this challenging time." The Government is in direct contact with the Fijians in Israel and can confirm that they are safe and accounted for. "Despite the unfortunate circumstances surrounding the conflict, we want to assure the families and loved ones of the 200 Fijians that their safety remains our utmost priority. We are closely monitoring the situation in Israel and are in regular communication with our citizens to provide them with any necessary support," Prime Minister Rabuka affirmed. "We are also aware of Fiji Airways' review of the scheduled flight to Tel Aviv on October 10. We will continue to coordinate with the airline and provide updates to the public as the situation evolves." The Government of Fiji urges all parties involved to seek a peaceful resolution to the conflict, and we call for an immediate cessation of hostilities to prevent further loss of life and suffering. "Our thoughts are with all those affected by this crisis, and we will continue to stand by the 200 Fijians in Israel to ensure their safety and well-being," Prime Minister Rabuka concluded. #peoplescoalition #FijiNews #GovernmentNews

üî¥ Israel restricts electricity, fuel, and goods to Gaza following an attack on Southern Israel, killing over 300 on Saturday.

I‚Äôm not going to sugarcoat it. There are some storms ahead. Some of them may hit this week, and they could have outsized implications for the nation, and even the world, going forward. Let‚Äôs take a look at three in particular.

**The Israel / Hamas war

On Saturday, in a surprise move, Hamas militants broke through Israel‚Äôs barriers in Gaza and committed several coordinated assaults upon Israeli armed forces as well as terrorist attacks upon civilians. There are hundreds dead and thousands wounded already on both sides. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu declared that Israel was now at war with Hamas, vowing and already initiating retaliation for the attacks.

The escalation into open warfare carries serious consequences and risks. The hostilities could bring other actors directly into conflict, including Hezbollah forces in Lebanon, backed by Iran. The unrest and fighting could spread to the West Bank, which is the other part of the Palestinian Territories. Far-right political factions in Israel could seize the moment politically to press their gains as the opposition, seeing the need for national unity, halts its protests over planned judicial ‚Äúreforms‚Äù that undermine democracy in the nation.

There is already political fallout in the U.S. as Republicans cast blame upon the Biden Administration for the attack, including falsely claiming that the $6 billion deal with Iran was to blame, even though that money remains unspent in an overseas account and is earmarked for humanitarian aid only. And progress on the Abraham Accords, which seek to establish further diplomatic relations between Israel and key Arab neighbors including Saudi Arabia, are likely on hold while civilian deaths within Gaza and Israel inevitably and tragically mount.

I will be writing a larger piece on Tuesday in The Big Picture substack, where I write once a week, to lay out the geopolitical concerns and risks that arise directly from this weekend‚Äôs events. As part of that, I‚Äôll set some context for why Hamas, which the U.S. has labeled a terrorist organization and which has called for the destruction of Israel, nevertheless enjoys broad support for its actions within the Arab world. At issue is the plight of the Palestinians in Gaza, including a long and sustained quarantining of the region and its two million inhabitants. I‚Äôll also walk through why achieving peace in the region is now very much harder given the bloody and brutal attack upon Israeli civilians committed by Hamas, which some are comparing to the 9/11 attacks on U.S. soil.

A word of caution: This is a very fraught subject that tends to divide U.S. progressives and thus even my readers here, and passions understandably run very high on all sides. Please be respectful in the comments and toward one another. My piece on Tuesday in The Big Picture will attempt to set out the facts and positions of the parties as objectively as possible, and most importantly to assess the political risks going forward, though I already know that it is nearly impossible to be seen as purely objective and dispassionate on this issue. I am not a Middle East expert, and after decades of watching others attempt to broker peace, I have no solutions to add. But I am well aware of the history and the arguments from all sides, and I can speak to the political impact of the war and what we in the U.S. should watch for.

To have my piece delivered to your inbox on Tuesday, be sure you are a subscriber to The Big Picture here. Our newsletter is free, but we always welcome and appreciate new paid supporters.

**Leaderless in the House, paralysis in the Senate

The escalation to war in Gaza comes at a time when the U.S. is facing a first in its history: the lack of a Speaker of the House. And over in the Senate, the antics of Senator Tommy Tuberville have left hundreds of key military positions unfilled. Add to that the fact that the Senate has yet to confirm Joe Biden‚Äôs nominee for ambassador to Israel, and it is fair to say the U.S. is far weaker than it should be in this time of crisis.

A Speaker is necessary to guide emergency funding bills for Israel through that chamber. The acting speaker pro tempore, Rep. Patrick McHenry (R-NC), lacks the power to move legislation through the body and is only a caretaker until an actual Speaker can be elected by majority vote. Currently, there are only two candidates declared for the position: Rep. Steve Scalise (R-LA), a staunch conservative who was in the No. 2 position in the conference before McCarthy was ousted, and Rep. Jim Jordan (R-OH), a MAGA extremist who heads the House Judiciary Committee. It is fairly clear that neither candidate has enough votes on his own to form a majority, so we will need to see after the first round of balloting how much support each actually has, and whether one will cede the race to the other.

Time is of the essence, however, not only to provide emergency aid to Israel, but also to head off a government (truncated)

Bangladesh calls for urgent ceasefire of armed conflicts between Israel and Palestine Bangladesh denounces the ongoing armed conflict between Israel and Palestine and deplores the resultant loss of innocent civilian lives and injury of victims. Bangladesh underlines that escalation of conflicts and violence benefits no party. We urge both Israeli and Palestinians to exercise maximum restraint and calls for immediate ceasefire to avoid further loss of innocent lives from both sides. Bangladesh holds that living under the Israeli occupation and forced settlements in Palestinian territory will not bring peace in the region. Therefore, Bangladesh supports a two-state solution, Palestine and Israel, living side by side as independent states free of occupation following UN Resolutions No. 242 and 338, which could bring lasting peace and stability in the region. Bangladesh also urges all parties concerned to refrain from excessive and indiscriminate use of force in the conflict and reiterates that only dialogue and diplomacy could lead to a lasting solution to the Israel-Palestine conflict and calls upon all parties to work towards this end.

‚ÄúCaptain Jack‚Äù, Kintpuash (c. 1837-1873) Modoc Tribe, Oregon and California Kintpuash was born near Tule Lake, an area that now straddles the Oregon-California border. The ancestral homeland of the Modoc Peoples consisted of 5,000 acres until 1864 when they were forcibly removed by the federal government to the lands of their neighbors on the newly-created Klamath Reservation. The Klamath was a much larger tribe than the Modoc, and conflict was inevitable. Now casually referred to as ‚ÄúCaptain Jack‚Äù by white colonizers, Kintpuash stood firm. In 1865 he led a band of Modoc from the reservation back to their lands in California. Four years went by before the United States army rounded them up again and back to Klamath territory, but Kintpuash was undaunted. In 1870 he marched back home again with 180 of his Modoc kinsmen. The government‚Äôs outright refusal to allow the Modoc back into their homelands led to the outbreak of the Modoc War from 1872 to 1873. Kintpuash fled with his band into the area now protected as the Lava Beds National Monument, and they settled into this natural fortress. His warriors made use of its many caves and trenches in the lava beds for defensive fighting, and women and children could be sheltered there. When the Modoc were finally located, the Army launched an attack on January 17, 1873. The US Army was beaten in this conflict but they weren‚Äôt retreating either. Kintpuash‚Äôs advisers suggested that the Army would leave if their warriors killed its leader General Edward Canby, (the future namesake of the town of Canby, Oregon) but Kintpuash hoped for a peaceful solution that would allow his people to stay in their territory. It wasn‚Äôt to be. During the next meeting of the peace commission on April 11, Kintpuash and several other Modoc broke down and drew pistols at a prearranged signal; he shot General Canby twice in the head. For this, he was executed on October 3, 1873. The area of the Lava Beds National Monument where Captain Jack and his men held out against the United States Army is now known as Captain Jack‚Äôs Stronghold. It took until 1984 for Kintpuash‚Äôs skull to be returned for proper reburial by his Modoc descendants. He is buried at Fort Klamath Park, Oregon.

The Holy Land, a place sacred to countless millions around the world, is currently mired in violence and suffering due to the prolonged political conflict and the lamentable absence of justice and respect for human rights. We, the Patriarchs and Heads of Churches in Jerusalem, have time and again appealed for the importance of respecting the historic and legal Status Quo of the holy shrines. In these trying times, we come together to raise our voices in unity, echoing the divine message of peace and love for all humanity. As custodians of the Christian faith, deeply rooted in the Holy Land, we stand in solidarity with the people of this region, who are enduring the devastating consequences of continued strife. Our faith, which is founded on the teachings of Jesus Christ, compels us to advocate for the cessation of all violent and military activities that bring harm to both Palestinian and Israeli civilians. We unequivocally condemn any acts that target civilians, regardless of their nationality, ethnicity, or faith. Such actions go against the fundamental principles of humanity and the teachings of Christ, who implored us to "love your neighbour as yourself" {Mark 12:31). It is our fervent hope and prayer that all parties involved will heed this call for an immediate cessation of violence. We implore political leaders and authorities to engage in sincere dialogue, seeking lasting solutions that promote justice, peace, and reconciliation for the people of this land, who have endured the burdens of conflict for far too long. In our capacity as spiritual leaders, we extend our hands to all those who suffer, and we pray that the Almighty may grant comfort to the afflicted, strength to the weary, and wisdom to those in positions of authority. We call upon the international community to redouble its efforts to mediate a just and lasting peace in the Holy Land, based on equal rights for all and on international legitimacy. Let us remember the words of the Apostle Paul: "For God is not a God of disorder but of peace" (1 Corinthians 14:33). In the spirit of this divine message, we implore all to work tirelessly towards an end to violence and the establishment of a just and lasting peace that will allow the Holy Land to be a beacon of hope, faith, and love for all. May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, the love of God, and the communion of the Holy Spirit be with us all during these challenging times. - The Patriarchs and Heads of the Churches in Jerusalem

Joan of Arc Was Excommunicated By The Same Church That Later Made Her A Saint Joan of Arc (or Jeanne d'Arc, as she was known in her native French) was a young warrior who claimed to have been sent by God to lead France to victory over England, most notably by helping the Dauphin Charles to be crowned king. Born in 1412, Joan began to experience intense religious visions at the age of 13. She described how the archangel Michael came to her, alongside St. Catherine and St. Margaret, and told her to consecrate her entire being to God. The voices Joan heard communicated that she was intended for a great purpose and that she was to help drive the English out of France in the conflict that would come to be known as the Hundred Years' War. The voices led her to seek out Charles and urge him to seek coronation. After many trials in which she was ridiculed and ignored, Joan finally got her chance for an audience. She won the support of Charles, and many others began to believe she was truly on a divine mission. With backing from French royalty, Joan set out on her campaign to liberate Orleans, dressed as a male for an extra measure of safety as she traveled through the wilds with only a small team of men to protect her. Joan went on to courageously lead troops to retake Orleans and push back the English in several key conflicts. Her bravery, devotion to God, and pious conduct inspired great morale in her followers, and before she turned 20, she blazed a trail that facilitated the crowning of the dauphin as Charles VII of France. Joan's visions and voices subsided, but she still refused to leave the battlefield. After a failed attempt to retake Paris, Joan was captured by the Burgundians at Compi√®gne and offered for ransom. Tragically, the same king she fought so hard for refused to pay the ransom. Joan was sold to the English and made to undergo a rigorous series of interrogations and trials. During this time, Joan was excommunicated by a bishop who seemed to think she was in league with satanic forces. Joan's protests and cries for divine assistance after this announcement were so heart-rending that many in the crowd, including an English cardinal, were seen weeping. Though Joan burned at the stake at the hands of her captors, her memory and heroism became immortal. In 1920, Joan was canonized and became a saint. Healthy boundaries will protect you from overextending yourself in life. They will also protect the health of your marriage when they're clearly defined. Here are a few ways you can tangibly create boundaries that protect your marriage, whilst also making sure you're BOTH on the same side of lines drawn: 1) Time. A lack of connected, quality time is the #1 issue couple's face today. It's ironic, since the world is more "connected" than ever. You must understand that your time is finite... you have a very limited amount. This means you must draw boundaries to block out wasteful or frivolous uses of it. Do this by turning off devices and spending quality time together. In 20 years, you won't remember what you read on social media but you will absolutely remember the moments you spend together. 2) Reconciliation. You will have arguments and fights, which means you will need to reconcile. Draw boundaries around the reconciliation process by agreeing not to bad-talk each other to friends or coworkers in ways that are destructive. It's good to seek counsel and advice, but venting anger to those outside your marriage is never helpful. Then, WITHIN the boundary of reconciliation, work together to resolve conflict in a biblical way. Talk, repent, forgive, make-up, and move on. 3) Integrity and transparency. Those without transparency live by themselves in a boundary they've created. They do this by engaging in wrong behavior and then hiding it (think: explicit websites, spending habits, emotional and physical affairs, eating habits). The first step toward living with integrity in your marriage is being transparent with each other. Open up the unhealthy boundaries and let your spouse in. If you have a secret other than a surprise gift, etc., then something is wrong. There are many boundaries we could discuss, but hopefully this will get you thinking. What are some other boundaries you have/shouldn't have in your life/marriage?

Thoughts on death. Eerie subject? Well, it depends on how you look at it. Actually, the fact of death reminds us to appreciate life even the more. Every second, your life span is reducing. Is this negative? No, it's true and important information. Life is precious because it ends, it's valuable because it's not eternal. In the field of economics, any commodity that is scarce, will have a high price. But life is priceless because it's irreplaceable. Is it easy to get another life if you waste this one? Actually, no one has died and come back to live again. There's no evidence of that. Once you're gone, that's it. You only have one shot at this. A well known African proverb says, "if you kill time, you bury opportunities." Meaning: when you waste time, you can never regain it. Many of us do not realize that actually - time is our life. In other words, our life is a period of time! Therefore, as we're spending time, we're spending life itself. Imagine if we lived knowing that every day, utilizing the value of every precious moment. How many times can we avoid unnecessary conflict with others? Maybe that's our problem as humanity. We think we have time. Meanwhile, we only have now. Tomorrow is not promised, but if it comes, receive it as a gift, and spend it wisely.

We publish below the communiqu√© (available in English and Arabic) of the Patriarchs and Heads of Churches in Jerusalem calling for peace and justice in the midst of the ongoing violence. *** The Patriarchs and Heads of Churches in Jerusalem unite in a Call for peace and justice amidst unfolding violence Jerusalem, october 7, 2023 The Holy Land, a place sacred to countless millions around the world, is currently mired in violence and suffering due to the prolonged political conflict and the lamentable absence of justice and respect for human rights. We, the Patriarchs and Heads of Churches in Jerusalem, have time and again appealed for the importance of respecting the historic and legal Status Quo of the holy shrines. In these trying times, we come together to raise our voices in unity, echoing the divine message of peace and love for all humanity. As custodians of the Christian faith, deeply rooted in the Holy Land, we stand in solidarity with the people of this region, who are enduring the devastating consequences of continued strife. Our faith, which is founded on the teachings of Jesus Christ, compels us to advocate for the cessation of all violent and military activities that bring harm to both Palestinian and Israeli civilians. We unequivocally condemn any acts that target civilians, regardless of their nationality, ethnicity, or faith. Such actions go against the fundamental principles of humanity and the teachings of Christ, who implored us to "love your neighbor as yourself" (Mark 12:31). It is our fervent hope and prayer that all parties involved will heed this call for an immediate cessation of violence. text: Today's A Mighty Girl Community Pick is in honor of Emily Blackwell's birthday: "The Doctors Blackwell: How Two Pioneering Sisters Brought Medicine to Women and Women to Medicine" by Janice P. Nimura. From an early age, Elizabeth Blackwell had an intense focus on breaking out of the confining limits placed on the aspirations of women of her day. Overcoming skepticism and deeply ingrained sexism, she became the first female physician in America, eventually winning over the male medical establishment with her diligence and keen intellect. Her sister Emily soon followed in her footsteps and the two founded the New York Infirmary for Indigent Women and Children, the first hospital staffed entirely by women. Both women were visionaries but their strongly held convictions and the fierce determination which allowed them to overcome centuries of discrimination against women in the medical profession also brought them into conflict at times. Even so, their partnership endured and together the sisters changed medicine forever by opening the doors for generations of female physicians after them. This richly researched biography tells the riveting story of the world-changing impact of these remarkable sisters, while providing an insightful look at the realities of 19th century medicine. Highly recommended for adult readers. Chief Crowfoot Crowfoot (1830 ‚Äì 25 April 1890) or Isapo-Muxika was a chief of the Siksika First Nation. His parents, Istowun-eh'pata (Packs a Knife) and Axkahp-say-pi (Attacked Towards Home), were Kainai. "Crowfoot stood and watched as the white man scattered many dollar bills on the floor. "This is what the white man trades in; this is his buffalo robe. As you trade pelts, we trade in these scraps of paper." When the white chief put all his money on the ground and showed how much he would give if the Indians would sign a treaty, Crowfoot took a handful of clay, made a ball out of it, and set it on the fire. He didn't break. So he said to the white man, Now put your money on the fire and see if it lasts as long as clay. The white man said, No... my money will burn because it's made of paper. With an amused gleam in his eyes the old chief said, Oh, your money isn't as good as our land, is it? The wind will blow the fire will burn it; the water will rot it. But nothing will destroy our land. You don't make a very good trade. Then, with a smile, Crowfoot took a handful of sand from the riverbank, handed it to the white man, and said: You count the grains of sand in it while I count the money you give for the land. The white man said, I wouldn't live long enough to count this, but you can count the money in a few minutes. Very well, said the wise Crowfoot, our land is more valuable than your money. It will last forever. It will not perish as long as the sun shines and the water flows, and throughout all the years it will give life to men and animals, so we cannot sell the land. It was placed there by the Great Spirit and we can't sell it because it doesn't really belong to us. You can count your money and burn it with a nod of a buffalo's head, but only the Great Spirit can count the grains of sand and blades of grass on these plains. As a gift, we'll give you anything you can take with you, but we can't give you the land. ‚Äù Crowfoot was a warrior who fought in as many as nineteen battles and sustained many injuries, but he tried to obtain peace instead of warfare. Crowfoot is well known for his involvement in Treaty Number 7 and did much negotiating for his people. While many believe Chief Crowfoot had no part in the North-West Rebellion, he did in fact participate to an extent due to his son's connection to the conflict. Crowfoot died of tuberculosis at Blackfoot Crossing on April 25, 1890. Eight hundred of his tribe attended his funeral, along with government dignitaries. In 2008, Chief Crowfoot was inducted into the North America Railway Hall of Fame where he was recognized for his contributions to the railway industry. Crowfoot is well known for his contributions to the Blackfoot nation, and has many memorials to signify his accomplishments.

On September 22, 1871, an elderly British lady, 82 years young, was ushered into her heavenly reward. Earlier in her life, in 1835, her frustration at being an invalid left her feeling useless and questioning her very salvation. What she did next would echo through history. As a young woman, Charlotte Elliot was not sure of her relationship with Christ, not sure of how to be saved, even though she had been raised a minister's daughter, and the probing question of a Swiss evangelist, ‚ÄúAre you at peace with God?‚Äù, would not leave her mind. When she saw the evangelist a few weeks later, she mentioned that she could not shake his question. But, she protested, what could she possibly bring to God? When he replied that she need not bring anything but herself, she gladly accepted Christ. Some twelve years later, in 1835, crippled by illness and constant fatigue, she felt saddened by her inability to help a local church‚Äôs cause. Remembering her conversion, she took out pen and paper and wrote a poem to encourage others who felt perhaps they too had nothing to give. . . "Just As I Am, without one plea, But that Thy blood was shed for me, And that Thou bidst me come to Thee, Oh, Lamb of God, I come..." Her poem was published and she was inundated with requests for it. She was gladdened to discover later that some copies were being sold to raise money for the very cause she felt helpless to assist! After her death, thousands of letters were found in her home, written by people whose lives had been transformed by her words. Her song has been translated into hundreds of languages, published in more than 1600 hymnals, and has reached billions around the world, and continues to bring people to Christ even today. On Oct. 1, 1931, a 31-year-old man riding in the sidecar of his brother's motorcycle in England finally came to the end of his internal struggle against whether Christ was indeed the Son of God. He finally knew in his soul that indeed Jesus was just who He said He was! He realized that God calls us to Him "just as we are". When C.S. Lewis stepped out of the sidecar, he was a new man, saved by grace! Ninety-nine years after Charlotte Elliott penned her words, and 3 years after Lewis‚Äô conversion, the 16-year-old son of a dairy farmer listened intently as he heard the message of salvation preached at a revival service in Charlotte, NC. When the song, ‚ÄúJust As I Am,‚Äù was sung at the end, young Billy Graham went forward to accept Christ. Twenty years later, Billy Graham had become a successful evangelist and was invited to speak at Cambridge University in England. His nervousness over the event nearly led him to cancel it. But he was introduced to a kind man named C.S. Lewis who encouraged him to disregard the critics who had spoken out against him, and to continue with the revival. Rev. Graham went on to speak to an overflow crowd of 2,000 each night of the revival, and when he returned to England in 1989, he addressed a crowd of 80,000 at England‚Äôs Wimbley Stadium! As always, he closed the event with the same song that brought him to Christ, ‚ÄúJust As I Am.‚Äù Never think you have ‚Äúnothing‚Äù to bring to Jesus! That is exactly what He wants you to bring... nothing! He wants you, just you, as you are! He can take frustration like Charlotte Elliot‚Äôs, skepticism like Lewis‚Äô, and nervousness like Billy Graham‚Äôs, and reach the world through you! "JUST AS I AM" 1 Just as I am, without one plea, But that Thy blood was shed for me, And that Thou bid‚Äôst me come to Thee, O Lamb of God, I come! I come! 2 Just as I am, and waiting not To rid my soul of one dark blot; To Thee whose blood can cleanse each spot, O Lamb of God, I come, I come! 3 Just as I am, though tossed about With many a conflict, many a doubt; Fightings within, and fears without, O Lamb of God, I come, I come! 4 Just as I am, poor, wretched, blind; Sight, riches, healing of the mind; Yes, all I need, in Thee to find, O Lamb of God, I come, I come! 5 Just as I am, Thou wilt receive, Wilt welcome, pardon, cleanse, relieve; Because Thy promise I believe, O Lamb of God, I come, I come! 6 Just as I am, Thy love unknown Has broken every barrier down; Now, to be Thine, yea, Thine alone, O Lamb of God, I come, I come! #WomenAtTheWell #JustAsIAm

I condemn Hamas‚Äô terrorist attack and fully support Israel‚Äôs right to defend itself. Those who would equivocate about who is at fault here, or conflate Hamas‚Äô savagery with more nuanced questions about the Israel-Palestinian conflict, are misguided. This is about Hamas, a group of violent religious extremists who have sworn to kill all Jews in Israel and beyond. One of the communities attacked yesterday is Kfar Aza, a kibbutz on the Gaza border that I visited last year. The Israelis I met were not rightwing settlers or zealots; they were thoughtful, compassionate people. Despite living under constant threat of Hamas rocket attacks, some of these folks worked for NGO‚Äôs doing humanitarian work in Gaza. Today‚Äôs media reports describe piles of bodies in Kfar Aza. The victims of Hamas‚Äô indiscriminate slaughter presumably include some of the wonderful, peace-loving people I met with. On the other side of the Gaza border, hundreds if not thousands of innocent Palestinians lives will be lost as Israel strikes back at Hamas. While I urge Israel to do everything possible to avoid and minimize the loss of innocent Palestinian lives, there will surely be collateral damage. Hamas has blood on its hands for these deaths too. I have profound disagreements with the Netanyahu government ‚Äì from its authoritarianism, to its undermining of the two-state solution, expansion of settlements and mistreatment of Palestinians in Jerusalem and the West Bank. I consider the occupation of the West Bank untenable and unjust. I support the rights and aspirations of the Palestinian people and will continue to push our ally Israel on these issues. Back from all day travel. I start by echoing a Jewish friend‚Äôs text to me: ‚ÄùI cry for each human life lost whether they be a Palestinian or a Jew. No Jew and no Muslim can celebrate the loss of a human being‚Äôs life.‚Äù Amen.

This should indeed be obvious to any reasonable, conscientious human being.

Having stated the obvious, sometimes it is necessary to state the apparently not-so-obvious: What is not so obvious to many is the following simple fact regarding this so-called conflict: there is one side occupying and one side occupied, one side beseiged and one side besieging, one side being forced into the world‚Äôs largest open air prison where basic human needs and rights are cut off making life unbearable if not unlivable, and one side living comfortably receiving billions of our tax dollars on top of it.

In the life to life view of things, yes no innocent life is worth more than the other; in the assessment of the conflict, there is no parity between the two sides. Moral equivocation between the occupier and occupied, the displacer and the displaced, the oppressor and the oppressed is but an accessory to the occupation, siege and oppression that are at the ‚Äúroot problem‚Äù of this conflict, and a master-spin campaign to victim-blame and whitewash the perpetrator. Americans who once had grievances against the British and took arms when oppressed know this more than anyone.

I add that if you are just remembering that every life matters today, but not last week, or last month, or last decade when Palestinians regularly lost lives to indiscriminate and arbitrary attacks or repressive policies then your morality today comes off as disingenuous and selective.

Violence is ugly, all of it. Gaslighting is also ugly. Double standards are ugly. For me this is not about team or tribe, never was. It‚Äôs about being fair even to those we deem week and dispensable - in this case the Palestinians. That is why I advocate for justice for Palestinians - because they are an oppressed people. Fair-minded Jews and Christians are right by my side.

The common canard that Palestinians inherently eschew violence, are pretending to be victims, put up human shields to bait the good ol‚Äô IDF, and must be oppressed because they can never be levelled with are all rooted in a racist dehumanizing campaign repeated by almost every Israeli prime minister and spokesperson. 

Palestinians are fighting for their freedom and dignity. And guess what: they wish they didn‚Äôt have to. They wish they could lounge in cushy malls instead - like you. That is the truth whether you like it or not. Ask yourself why that is easy to understand with Ukrainians or other White groups contemporaneously and historically, but never with Brown and Black ones.  

I really hope that we, the American people, can wake up and stop being fodder - witting or unwitting - for propaganda. That we can push our officials to work for peace between fellow human beings, instead of parroting dumbed-down gimmicky canards, and to understand that peace can only be rooted in justice. 

Praying for true peace.

War is hell. I‚Äôve experienced it firsthand throughout my time in the Marine Corps and multiple deployments. I have seen the death and destruction that it creates and felt its lasting effects long after returning home. In war, there are no winners. None. I believe that at the very core of who I am. And so I am left to ask, ‚ÄúWhy?‚Äù Why do some feel like conflict is the only solution? The United States is a nation born of many values - the best of which we continue to hold dear in America. Life, liberty, the pursuit of happiness, and freedom. These values are not afforded to the Palestinian people and I remain resolute in my belief that the Palestinian people deserve the same rights that we are afforded in America. To be clear, my support for Palestine is just that. I support Palestinian self-determination because I am pro-humanitarian and anti-extremism, both at home and abroad. I do not subscribe to the belief that opposing the subjugation of Palestinians equates to being anti-Jewish. I am joined in that belief by hundreds of thousands of Jewish Israelis who support Palestinian independence and even more Muslims and Christians here in America who are proud to call Jewish men and women our brothers and sisters. I am proud to count myself among them. When international conflicts of this magnitude are taking place, we see others run to the quickest and easiest soundbites to try and make their point on social media and beyond. It does an incredible injustice to the nuance and reality of what is happening in real time. I won‚Äôt allow it here. The loss of innocent lives - no matter one‚Äôs race, religion, or country of origin - is and always will be unacceptable. Any role that the United States seeks to play in this conflict should seek to minimize the loss of life and must only come through diplomatic measures - not through the provision of military aid, equipment, or funding. To be sure, the quickest way to end this violence is to end the illegal occupation and apartheid of Palestine and the Palestinian people. The United States can and should play a role in brokering that peace - a peace that must bring justice and equality to all people. It is in this pursuit of justice and peace that lies the ‚Äúwhy.‚Äù None of us - not a single one of us - would accept the life that is forced upon the Palestinian people. An inability to vote. An inability to access healthcare. An inability to see your family. An inability to travel freely or leave your home. Forced to walk on the other side of the street. Unable to pray in your house of worship - or worse still, murdered while you‚Äôre praying within it. The fear of waking up one day and having your home taken from you without rhyme or reason. Paying taxes without representation in the government that dictates your standard of living and quality of life. 1776 is calling - Americans would never accept what the Palestinians are forced to endure. So why do we sit silent and turn a blind eye? There are some that want you to believe that the actions that has taken place over the last few days are unprovoked. I reject this attempt to further turn international sentiment against the Palestinian people. For decades, the international community seems to have lost its tongue. To ignore the facts that have led up to these events - facts that have been playing out before our very eyes for decades - will further jeopardize the response of the international community, and risk the potential of further inflaming events in the region. I love the United States and the opportunities that it provides to all who live here. We cannot run from or ignore our history and the fact that the United States was founded on violence and bloodshed. That founding is glorified in our textbooks, at events and political rallies throughout the country today, on t-shirts and flags, and across social media. Why then do we clutch our pearls in disgust when others seek to achieve their freedoms through the same means and methodology? We are a country born of revolution. It‚Äôs illogical to believe we are and will be the only ones. I will always condemn violence and the loss of life. I hate war and the death and destruction that it brings and the profiteering that is enjoyed by the military industrial complex. The Palestinian people seek to live in freedom, and I believe it‚Äôs time to end the occupation to bring about a just and lasting peace in the region.

Remembering Josef Franti≈°ek and the Czech WW2 fighter pilots serving in Polish Squadrons A daring airman who became the highest-scoring RAF ace during the Battle of Britain. He was a Czech in service with the Polish 303 Squadron. His name was Josef Franti≈°ek. 17 confirmed kills achieved in a month was an impressive score. Although he was a great pilot and a great marksman, he lacked discipline and showed an individualistic attitude which wasn‚Äôt necessarily something his superiors appreciated. In order to hunt the enemy alone, he would often separate from the squadron in flight. Throughout his duty, in the 303 Squadron Franti≈°ek remained loyal to his Polish comrades. When he was proposed to join a Czech squadron, he declined stating that ‚Äúhe is a Pole‚Äù. Franti≈°ek had a strong bond with Poland, as he was one of the Czech airman who left Czechoslovakia in 1939 to join the Polish Air Forces, and later defended Poland from the German invasion. Even though he perished during the early stages of the conflict, Josef Franti≈°ek is considered as one of the best fighter pilots of the WW2 era. Today is the 80th anniversary of his death. On 8 October 1940, he crashed his Hurricane while doing a low pass in Surrey. He was killed instantly. Did you know that Josef Franti≈°ek wasn‚Äôt the only Czech flying with the Polish squadrons during the Battle of Britain? At that time, except for him, there were three Czech airmen in service with the Polish fighter units. What is interesting is that they all were friends. Poles nicknamed them the ‚ÄúCzech Cloverleaf". Wilhelm Kosarz was born in Karvina, Czechoslovakia. He moved to Poland in 1926 and became a successful sports pilot, flying with Jerzy Bajan‚Äôs aerobatic team. He was assigned to 302 Squadron. He was killed in action exactly a month after Franti≈°ek‚Äôs death, on 8 November 1940, shot down by a Bf109. Matej Pavloviƒá - a Czech airman flying with the 303 Squadron. He was killed in action in April 1941 over France, shot down by a Bf109. Josef Balejka ‚Äì the only one who survived the war. He flew with the 303 Squadron and after the war, just like many of his Polish colleagues, he remained in exile. Balejka returned to Czechoslovakia when communism was about to fall. The assault marked one of the most devastating attacks on Israel in recent history, hinting at intelligence lapses and jeopardizing the perceived invulnerability of the country's security systems. Hamas, backed by a barrage of thousands of rockets, successfully breached Israel's defense barrier and unleashed chaos on nearby towns and communities. Beyond the vast number of casualties, which the nation hasn't seen in decades, over 300 Palestinians in Gaza also lost their lives. The aftermath of the attack saw militants abducting numerous captives, including women, children, and the elderly, back to Gaza. It is believed that Hamas intends to negotiate a trade with these hostages for Palestinian prisoners in Israeli detention. Highlighting the gravity of the situation, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced the nation was officially at war and vowed retaliation. ‚ÄúThis war will take time. It will be difficult,‚Äù Netanyahu cautioned, adding that Hamas will face severe repercussions for their actions. On Saturday, during the extensive and shocking assault, Hamas utilized diverse means to infiltrate Israel ‚Äî from explosives at the border fence to paragliders and speed boats on the coast. Their forces spread to various locations outside Gaza, as far as 15 miles from the border, while concurrently launching rocket barrages at Israeli urban areas. Israeli countermeasures resulted in massive bombardments on Gaza, targeting 426 sites, causing large-scale destruction. The Palestinian Health Ministry confirmed 313 deaths in Gaza, including 20 children, with approximately 2,000 wounded. Simultaneously, tensions heightened on Israel's northern border with Lebanon, where skirmishes with the Hezbollah militant group provoked concerns of a more extensive regional conflict. Despite the carnage, both sides seem prepared for prolonged engagement. Netanyahu urged Gaza's residents to evacuate, a call largely symbolic given the strict blockade imposed on the territory since Hamas took control in 2007. In a stark retaliation, Israel cut off electricity to Gaza, plunging much of the region into darkness. Hamas' leadership signaled their readiness for a protracted conflict. ‚ÄúWe are prepared for all options, including all-out war,‚Äù stated Saleh al-Arouri, the deputy head of the Hamas political bureau. Global reactions to the conflict have been swift. President Joe Biden expressed support for Israel, emphasizing its right to self-defense. In contrast, Iran's President Ebrahim Raisi lauded the incursion, speaking directly with Hamas and Islamic Jihad leadership. The trigger for the attack, termed "Operation Al-Aqsa Storm" by Hamas, is believed to be multifaceted. For over a year, tensions have risen due to Israeli settlement expansions in the occupied West Bank and mounting violence from Israeli settlers. Furthermore, frictions surrounding the Al-Aqsa mosque in Jerusalem, a historically sensitive site, have exacerbated the situation. As the region teeters on the brink, international efforts are underway to mediate, with Egypt playing a pivotal role, though initial endeavors hint at a challenging road ahead to restore peace.
