If you don't let your negative emotion out it just eats you up from within, there is a growling dog within you for hours. The fire has to burn the fire, one just has to burn in the emotion till the fire dies down and becomes balanced. The burning of the fire, of the emotion, cannot be tricked out of one's system; there is no recipe for getting rid of it, it has to be endured. The fire has to burn until the last unclean element has been consumed, which is what all alchemical texts say in different variations, and we have not found any other way either. It cannot be hindered but only suffered till what is mortal or corruptible, or, as our text says so beautifully, till the corruptible humidity, the unconsciousness, has been burnt up. That is the meaning, it is the acceptance of suffering. If one is filled with 10,000 devils one can only be burnt up in them until they quiet down and are still, and the infantile demand on the analyst or anybody else, that he should redeem one with some kind of comforting trick, does not help. If an analyst pretends he can do that, then he is just a quack, because there is no such thing, and anyway it would be meaningless. If he tries to get analysands out of the suffering it means he takes away from them what is most valuable; cheap comforting is wrong, for by that you get people away from the heat, the place where the process of individuation takes place. Sitting in Hell and roasting there is what brings forth the philosopher's stone. The unconscious itself, as pure nature, has an inner balance. The lack of balance comes from the childishness of the conscious attitude. If you only follow your own passion according to its own indications it will never go too far, it will always lead to its own defeat. Inordinate passion seeks defeat. People who have an inordinately passionate nature, a kind of devilish nature, are lovingly searching for a human person, or a situation, against which they can knock their heads, and they despise any partner or situation in which their passion wins out. Instinctively they seek defeat. It is as though something within them knows this devil has to be hit on the head, which is why if one is friendly or weak, or understanding towards such fire, one does not help the person; generally such people walk out on you, because that is not what they want. The fire of the passion looks for that which will extinguish it, and that is why the urge for individuation, as long as it is a natural inordinate urge, seeks impossible situations; it seeks conflict and defeat and suffering because it seeks its own transformation. - Marie-Louise von Franz, Alchemy: An Introduction to the Symbolism and the Psychology (Inner City Books 1980), pp. 252-254. The urge and compulsion to self-realization is a law of nature and thus of invincible power, even though its effect, at the start, is insignificant and improbable. - C.G. Jung, The Psychology of the Child Archetype, CW 9i: Archetypes and the Collective Unconscious, par. 289. Art: Crow's Song, by Andrea Kowch

"Ijebu Ode History" Ijebu also known as Jebu or Geebu is a Yoruba kingdom in Nigeria. It was formed around the fifteenth century. According to legend, its ruling dynasty was founded by Obanta whose personal name was Ogborogan of Ile-Ife. Its contemporary successor is one of the country's traditional states. The kingdom was one of the most developed in the region with a complex and highly organized government. The capital is at Ijebu Ode where the Awujale has his palace. Counterbalancing the Awujale is the Osugbo (known as the Ogboni in other parts of Nigeria), a council of all free born, titled men that acted as the kingdom's courts. The Osugbo is divided into six groups based on rank, the highest being the iwarefa, whose head the Oliwa was the second most powerful figure in the nation. Also powerful is the Olisa, who could be described as the mayor of Ijebu Ode. The Kingdom was made up of several towns and stretches to parts of Lagos State and borders Ondo State. The state rose in power in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, mainly due to its important position on the trade routes between Lagos and Ibadan. The kingdom imposed sharp limits on trade, insisting that all trade through the region be conducted by Ijebu merchants. The monopoly brought great wealth to the kingdom, but also annoyed the Europeans. In 1892, the British Empire declared war on the Ijebu kingdom in response to its barriers on trade. The British emerged victorious in the conflict and captured the Ijebu capital, burning the meeting hall of the Osugbo. As noted by colonial governor Frederick Lugard, 1st Baron Lugard, the British made efficient use of the Maxim gun during the conflict; when Lugard defended himself in response to criticism of the high casualties rates caused by Maxim guns employed by troops under his command during military campaigns in the Uganda Protectorate, he stated: "On the West Coast, in the 'Jebu' war, undertaken by Government, I have been told 'several thousands' were mowed down by the Maxim." After British colonization, the capital served as an administrative center for colonial officials as the kingdom was annexed to the colony of Southern Nigeria. Today, it constitutes one of the traditional states of Nigeria. The Ijebu kingdom is governed by a king and his group of titled elders, who usually are men of a higher status and of considerable influence. The council governed the region and had representatives of further devolved councils who no longer have any power. Since the invasion of Lord Lugard, these councils have continued to meet and advise the Obanta kings, their power, however, is largely ceremonial since the establishment of the colonial administration in their protectorate. The elders were known to represent their various villages and the will of the people, and are now not such a significant part in the ceremonial process. The elders were all given individual titles and the lead elder was given the title prince, although he was only ever to inherit the kingship in special circumstances. The traditional belief that governed the monarchy was similar to that of the Chinese Mandate of Heaven. The Ijebu Kingdom is estimated to be one of the earliest kingdoms founded in the African rain forest. Ijebu-Ode was originally a city founded by a leader from Ife. Like most other early states in the Yoruba region, they began to build a series of walls and ditches around the city, construction of these walls began in 800‚Äì1000 AD when the walls were called Sungbo‚Äôs Eredo. The walls extended to eventually cover the entirety of the Ijebu kingdom. It was massive with an estimated 3.5 million cubic meters of moved earth and sand and is among the largest man-made monuments in Africa. The evidence found is not linked to an isolated townbut to a kingdom‚Äôs large dike, a kingdom which was once functional and had at its disposal a high level of agricultural practice, an established pottery-making tradition, and possibly an army that triggered the construction of the Eredo. Further archeological works show the advancement of the Ijebu kingdom, the palace of the capital, Ijebu-Ode was shown to have the floors paved with ceramic pavements. People at the palace also seemed to practice astronomy with triangular pavements facing a true eastern direction; it extreme aligns to the movement of the sun from one solar solstice to the other one and worked as a sundial. Europeans also had a first hand account of Ijebu and wrote about it. Portuguese sailors and traders on the West African coast encountered the Ijebu kingdom first in which they called Geebu in the 1508...

The Quechan (or Yuma) (Quechan: Kwats√°an 'those who descended') are an aboriginal American tribe who live on the Fort Yuma Indian Reservation on the lower Colorado River in Arizona and California just north of the Mexican border. Despite their name, they are not related to the Quechua people of the Andes. Members are enrolled into the Quechan Tribe of the Fort Yuma Indian Reservation. The federally recognized Quechan tribe's main office is located in Winterhaven, California. Its operations and the majority of its reservation land are located in California, United States. The historic Yuman-speaking people in this region were skilled warriors and active traders, maintaining exchange networks with the Pima in southern Arizona, New Mexico, and with peoples of the Pacific coast. The first significant contact of the Quechan with Europeans was with the Spanish explorer Juan Bautista de Anza and his party in the winter of 1774. Relations were friendly. On Anza's return from his second trip to Alta California in 1776, the chief of the tribe and three of his men journeyed to Mexico City to petition the Viceroy of New Spain for the establishment of a mission. The chief Palma and his three companions were baptized in Mexico City on February 13, 1777. Palma was given the Spanish baptismal name Salvador Carlos Antonio. Spanish settlement among the Quechan did not go smoothly; the tribe rebelled from July 17‚Äì19, 1781 and killed four priests and thirty soldiers. They also attacked and damaged the Spanish mission settlements of San Pedro y San Pablo de Bicu√±er and Puerto de Pur√≠sima Concepci√≥n, killing many. The following year, the Spanish retaliated with military action against the tribe. After the United States annexed the territories after winning the Mexican‚ÄìAmerican War, it engaged in the Yuma War from 1850 to 1853 in response to a conflict between the Quechan and Jaeger's Ferry and the Glanton Gang, after the Quechan had established a rival ferry service on the Colorado River. During which, the historic Fort Yuma was built across the Colorado River from the present day Yuma, Arizona. Pic: Quechan men in western Arizona - circa 1875

The United Church of Canada Calls for Immediate Ceasefire in Israel and Palestine: The United Church mourns the deaths and injuries already suffered and calls for an immediate ceasefire to the recent escalation in violence in Israel and Palestine. The United Church condemns the attacks launched on communities in southern Israel by Hamas, and the ongoing daily violence meted out against Palestinians by Israel's deepening occupation in Palestinian territories. Echoing the statement issued by the World Council of Churches, The United Church of Canada is deeply concerned about the risks of spiralling conflict between Palestinian armed groups and Israeli forces, which impacts civilians on both sides the most and only leads to further violence and suffering. "We pray for the victims and the families of those killed, injured, and abused," said Rev. Michael Blair, General Secretary of The United Church of Canada. The United Church joins with all those praying for a just peace in the Holy Land and urges global leaders to work urgently for an end to the current violence, an end to the ongoing occupation of Palestinian territories, and a just and lasting peace for Palestinians and Israelis. ISRAEL DECLARES STATE OF WAR FOLLOWING GAZA ROCKET ATTACKS In a dramatic escalation of the ongoing conflict, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu declared Israel to be "at war" on Saturday. This declaration came after Palestinian militants from Gaza launched a deadly barrage of rockets and sent gunmen into Israeli territory. The Israeli military reported that approximately 2,200 rockets were fired from the Gaza Strip into Israel, while armed terror groups used unconventional means to infiltrate Israel via land, sea, and even paragliders. Explosions resonated across Jerusalem, Tel Aviv, and southern Israel, with some blasts attributed to the interception of incoming rockets. Air raid sirens prompted Israelis to seek refuge in underground shelters. The Israel Defense Forces (IDF) disclosed that Hamas had taken "hostages and prisoners of war," without specifying numbers. Israel reported at least 200 fatalities and 1,452 injuries, as per Israel's emergency rescue service and health ministry. In response, Israel initiated airstrikes targeting what it referred to as Hamas sites within Gaza. The Palestine Tower, a high-rise building in Gaza City housing residential apartments and media offices, was struck by an explosion and subsequently collapsed, as depicted in videos. The Palestinian health ministry reported 232 Palestinian casualties and 1,697 injuries. However, details regarding the locations of the deaths and whether the toll encompassed Hamas militants or Gaza civilians were not provided. Netanyahu announced that operations were underway to "clear communities that have been infiltrated by terrorists" and declared a call-up of reservists. ‚ÄúMajesty Surfacing‚Äù / Brown bears are generally solitary creatures, but when fall comes, and the salmon return to the Yukon's rivers, these nomads are forced to crowd into close proximity. Each one has their preferred fishing technique: some are divers, some pounce, others charge up the middle of the river, and some wait stealthily on rocks. In the case of Morris the bear, his preferred method was to ‚Äúsnorkel‚Äù with his face submerged in the river and his ears free to detect potential threats. Tensions can run high as the bears all vie for the best fishing spots. Keeping an ear out for any unruly neighbors while pursuing salmon is a clever way to avoid conflict. However, as threats like runoff, development, and disease from local salmon farms undermine the future of the once-abundant fish, bears like Morris will have an even harder time surviving. In order to safeguard Canada‚Äôs wildlife and its fragile ecosystems, we must protect wild salmon.

The death toll from the powerful magnitude-6.3 earthquake and subsequent aftershocks in western Afghanistan has tragically surpassed 2,000, marking one of the deadliest earthquakes to hit the country in the past two decades. As we come to grips with this devastating loss, we must remember that death tolls tend to climb when information trickles in from more remote areas, where decades of conflict have left infrastructure in disrepair, making relief and rescue efforts exceedingly challenging.

Moreover, Afghanistan's healthcare system, heavily dependent on foreign aid, has suffered profound cuts in the two years since the Taliban assumed control, causing significant disruptions to the economy, including the cessation of vital international assistance.

In these trying times, let us unite in solidarity, keeping the victims and the people of Afghanistan in our thoughts and prayers. Additionally, please consider contributing whatever you can to support humanitarian efforts in this critical time of need.

Once again, the world is witnessing a war where civilians pay the price for the short-sightedness and greed of their leaders.

The photo from Samar Abu Elouf of the New York Times shows children in Gaza yesterday looking toward the sky at Israeli warplanes that are bombing their land while they are unable to leave. For context on this "war" that is largely ignored by the US media, I recommend a report from Amnesty International about how Israel for years has violated international law by imposing a system of apartheid on Palestinians that violates their fundamental human rights. The report, which has been endorsed by prominent human rights groups around the world including many in Israel, can be read via the link in the bio.

To be clear, the targeting of civilians by combatants is a war crime and I condemn it no matter who the perpetrator. But there is a reason that I as an American Jew and millions of others have felt deeply disturbed by the failure of the Israeli government to live up to its promise. In short, Israel is not a democracy; it is an apartheid regime that treats Palestinians as an inferior racial group defined by their status as Arabs and non-Jews. The country's laws enshrine discrimination. Palestinians are not allowed either citizenship or nationality. This is not dissimilar to what the US government did to deny freedoms to blacks and other people of color until our own system of legalized apartheid was dismantled. 

Amnesty documents how Israel targets Palestinians by engaging in unlawful killings, detention without trial, massive land theft, and forced displacement and statelessness. To cite one example of the brutality, in 2019 Israeli snipers killed 214 Palestinian civilians including 46 children when they protested near the fence that makes Gaza the world's largest open-air prison. Two million people, including the children above, are trapped by Israel in a 25-mile strip of land.

There will be no hope of a sustainable peace if Israel's system of apartheid is not ended such that all living in that territory can enjoy equal rights under the law. Solidarity with all civilians caught in the conflict. ‚òÆÔ∏è‚òÆÔ∏è

Air India on Sunday said it has cancelled its flights to and from Tel Aviv till October 14. Israel came under attack by Hamas on Saturday and since then, both sides are engaged in fighting in which scores of people have died. ‚ÄúOur flights to and from Tel Aviv will remain suspended till 14th October, 2023, for the safety of our passengers and crew,‚Äù an airline spokesperson said in a statement.

The airline will extend all possible support to passengers who have confirmed bookings on any flight during this period, the spokesperson added. The full service carrier operates five weekly flights to Tel Aviv from the national capital. The service is on Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday and Sunday. On Saturday also, the carrier cancelled its flights to and from Tel Aviv.

‚ÄúKenya joins the rest of the world in solidarity with the State of Israel and unequivocally condemn terrorism and attacks on innocent civilians in the country. Kenya strongly maintains that there exists no justification whatsoever for terrorism, which constitutes a serious threat to international peace and security,‚Äù he asserted on X (formerly Twitter).

Ruto reiterated that all acts of terrorism and violent extremism are abhorrent, criminal, and unjustifiable, regardless of the motives behind them. 

He further called upon the international community to swiftly mobilize and hold not only the attackers but also their organizers, financiers, and supporters accountable for their actions.

The Head of state also called for immediate cessation of violence.

"In consideration of the complex and delicate context of the security situation in Israel-Palestine, Kenya also makes a call for the de-escalation of violence and urges all parties to restrain from further military action, given its potential to intensify carnage and the suffering of innocent civilians, and to trigger heightened tension in the region and beyond,‚Äù he posited.

List of major wars and conflicts between Israel and Arab states:

1. 1948 Arab-Israeli War (First Arab-Israeli War): Fought immediately after the declaration of the State of Israel in 1948, involving Arab states including Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon, and Iraq.

2. Suez Crisis (1956): A conflict primarily involving Egypt, the United Kingdom, France, and Israel, triggered by Egypt's nationalization of the Suez Canal.

3. Six-Day War (1967): Israel fought against Egypt, Jordan, and Syria, resulting in Israel gaining control of the Sinai Peninsula, West Bank, and Golan Heights.

4. War of Attrition (1967-1970): A series of skirmishes and battles along the Suez Canal and the Israeli-Egyptian border.

5. Yom Kippur War (1973): Egypt and Syria launched a surprise attack on Israel during Yom Kippur, leading to a ceasefire.

6. Lebanon War (1982): Israel invaded Lebanon to remove the Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) from southern Lebanon, also involving Syrian forces.

7. First Intifada (1987-1993): A Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.

8. Second Intifada (2000-2005): Another Palestinian uprising against Israeli occupation, marked by increased violence.

9. Lebanon War (2006): A conflict between Israel and Hezbollah, a Shiite militant group based in Lebanon.

10. Gaza-Israel Conflicts (Various): Ongoing conflicts between Israel and Palestinian groups in the Gaza Strip, including Hamas and Islamic Jihad, with notable events like Operation Cast Lead (2008-2009), Operation Pillar of Defense (2012), and Operation Protective Edge (2014).

List of major wars and conflicts between Israel and Arab states:

1. 1948 Arab-Israeli War (First Arab-Israeli War): Fought immediately after the declaration of the State of Israel in 1948, involving Arab states including Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon, and Iraq.

2. Suez Crisis (1956): A conflict primarily involving Egypt, the United Kingdom, France, and Israel, triggered by Egypt's nationalization of the Suez Canal.

3. Six-Day War (1967): Israel fought against Egypt, Jordan, and Syria, resulting in Israel gaining control of the Sinai Peninsula, West Bank, and Golan Heights.

4. War of Attrition (1967-1970): A series of skirmishes and battles along the Suez Canal and the Israeli-Egyptian border.

5. Yom Kippur War (1973): Egypt and Syria launched a surprise attack on Israel during Yom Kippur, leading to a ceasefire.

6. Lebanon War (1982): Israel invaded Lebanon to remove the Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) from southern Lebanon, also involving Syrian forces.

7. First Intifada (1987-1993): A Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.

8. Second Intifada (2000-2005): Another Palestinian uprising against Israeli occupation, marked by increased violence.

9. Lebanon War (2006): A conflict between Israel and Hezbollah, a Shiite militant group based in Lebanon.

10. Gaza-Israel Conflicts (Various): Ongoing conflicts between Israel and Palestinian groups in the Gaza Strip, including Hamas and Islamic Jihad, with notable events like Operation Cast Lead (2008-2009), Operation Pillar of Defense (2012), and Operation Protective Edge (2014).

I would like to conclude with an image from Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) in northern Kenya and ask us all the question: If they have done so much with hope, resilience, and imagination, what might we reimagine together? 

 Reteti is changing the lives of both elephants and people. This extraordinary group does so much to rescue, rehabilitate and rewild elephant calves that are orphaned as a result of drought, human-wildlife conflict, natural mortality, and in rare cases, poaching. Here, Mary Lengees comforts one of the calves. 

Elephants are a keystone species and ‚Äúecosystem engineers‚Äù because they shape habitats in a multitude of ways. They are huge mobile composting units and create water sources in dry landscapes by digging wells with their tusks. They move seeds across huge landscapes and clear paths through dense vegetation that ultimately benefits other animals and people.We need them for our own survival.

Here's the hard truth about love and relationships - they require transparency. 

Radical fucking honesty. 

But this can be a massive challenge when we struggle to be honest with ourselves, never mind another person.

Sex, communication, and boundaries....
All of these things can be radically impacted by how our shadow (what we hide or reject about ourselves) and how it show up in our relationship. 

But we do this for good reason. Often we are trying to prove/uplhold an image of who we think we need to be (or who we think they want us to be), or because the idea of being honest/transparent will lead to rejection, embarrassment, or conflict. 

For example:
We can get angry and act from a hostile place simply because we have felt rejected or embarrassed, but don't know how to communicate it. 

As I've said in many men‚Äôs groups, it's easier for a man to say "Fuck you" than "that fucking hurt" without turning into the victim or the martyr. 

Part of our work in relationships, and in life, is to begin to face the unsavoury aspects of our own internal nature. 

And this can be challenging because to do so is to risk looking and feeling like a damn fool sometimes. 

It's almost easier to stay in the comfort zone of sabotage and ignorance than it is to enter into the valley of the unknown and explore our deeper patterns. 

But this is also where we find the gold of life: strength, resiliency, self-direction and so forth. 

All of these virtues are crafted in our willingness to face our darkness.

Women of Amfissa (c. 1887)
By
Lawrence Alma-Tadema (1836‚Äì1912) 

Lawrence Alma-Tadema's "Women of Amfissa" (c. 1887) is a captivating historical painting that vividly brings to life an ancient Greek tale recounted by the renowned author Plutarch. This masterpiece depicts a poignant moment of moral significance.

In the painting, we see the turmoil of war between the inhabitants of Phocide and Amphisissa as the backdrop. However, the focal point of the artwork revolves around a group of Bacchantes from Phocis. These Bacchantes, having been enraptured by their nocturnal ritual dances in honor of Dionysus, have inadvertently wandered into enemy territory, falling asleep exhausted without realizing their location.

The morning light reveals the Bacchantes in a state of shock and fear as they awaken in the bustling market square of Amphissa, surrounded by their adversaries. The vulnerability of these women is palpable as they face imminent danger from the hostile Amphisissan forces.

Yet, the heartwarming essence of the painting lies in the response of the women of Amphissa. They gather around the weary and frightened Bacchantes, extending their protection and offering them shelter and nourishment. Their faces bespeak compassion and empathy as they plead with their husbands and fellow townsfolk not to harm these defenseless strangers. This remarkable act of compassion and the spirit of humanity prevailing over the ravages of war serve as the central theme of Alma-Tadema's "Women of Amfissa."

Through his meticulous attention to detail, the artist not only captures the historical setting but also conveys the timeless message of kindness and the possibility of unity even in the midst of conflict. The painting stands as a testament to the enduring power of empathy and the potential for goodness to shine through in the most challenging of circumstances.

Jedburgh is one of the four great abbeys established in the Scottish Borders in the 1100s. David I founded a priory here in 1138 and raised it to abbey status in 1154. The brethren may have come here from St Quentin Abbey, near Beauvais, France.

Augustinians were priests who for the most part lived a secluded and contemplative life, but also went forth to minister to the people.

Monastic life was largely routine. But the abbey‚Äôs border location meant it was caught up in the conflict between Scotland and England in the later Middle Ages. The canons had to evacuate the premises during the Wars of Independence in the 1300s.

Our special Exhibition ‚ÄûGermany at Sea‚Äú provides an overview of the 175 years of history of the German Navies. It is displayed on Deck 1 of the Museum until November the 5th 2023. One of the displays focuses on the importance on the development of the submarine weapon for the navy of the German Imperial Navy since the beginning of the 20th Century and during World War I. The display also explains the propagandistic dimension of the use of submarines during the war and also contains this astonishing model.

Submarine ‚ÄúU 96‚Äù, 1917
¬†
As late as the beginning of 1915, the German naval authorities assumed that the war would soon be over. Large U-boats, which took far more than a year to complete, seemed only conditionally necessary for a war decision. They were part of longer-term planning for a threat against Britain beyond a war‚Äôs end. Things turned out differently, however. The conflict continued, and by mid-1915 naval surface ships, except for a few raiders, were no longer present on the world‚Äôs oceans. The submarines were engaged in commercial warfare alone. Those of type ‚ÄúU 96‚Äù to ‚ÄúU 98‚Äù were ordered on September 15, 1915. They were boats of 837 tons displacement and 71.5 meters length. They carried six torpedo tubes and a 10.5 cm gun; their diving depth was 50 meters. ‚ÄúU 96,‚Äù commissioned in April 1917, sunk 31 merchant ships under the command of lieutenant Heinrich Je√ü and was scrapped at Bo‚Äôness in 1920.

Years later, John settles into his life as an educator at Jacksonville‚Äôs nationally renowned school for the deaf, and Mary is a gardener in Springfield for handsome, wealthy Edward Moore. MARK VAN WAGNER @mark.van 

Underground, 2023.
Natural and pigmented sand, debris glue gesso on cardboard box
30"x23"x4"

In combining movement with stillness, Mark Van Wagner‚Äôs artworks reference and combine various archeological, architectural, anthropomorphic characteristics, and various investigations of the inner and outer landscape. His sculptures often depict moments of impact and reverberations of force. 
The implications of conflict and ruin are present but so are humor and restoration, providing a sense of intimacy and introspection for the embodied subject.

Over the years, Van Wagner has collected natural sand from around the world and combines this substance along with flotsam and pigmented sand onto his layered-relief sculptures. In the exploration of applying mixed-media/assemblage into his artwork, he has recognized sand to be the most literal medium to capture material decomposition - its essence defining impermanence related to time, place and gross matter. Thick and thin spontaneous-gestural applications of glue adhesives and gesso are sprinkled with innumerable sand particles and debris over manipulated cardboard boxes. By reassembling the sand back into a concrete substance and onto his humble armatures his work playfully reminds us of life‚Äôs cycles.

We sensed that we were saying ‚ÄúI do‚Äù to big things like sickness and poverty and when facing significant challenges.

To all my concerned friends who are asking if I'm safe and okay, I need you to know I'm safe, but I am far from okay. The situation here is terrible. I'm using the term 'here' because every word, name or term that divides our territories only adds fuel to this crisis.

I can't escape the heartbreaking videos‚ÄîIsraeli citizens, including the elderly and children, being kidnapped and murdered, and Gaza's citizens, also children, are being killed, illegally arrested or living in fear of relentless bombings. And then there are those voices of these influencers from both sides, trying to explain who's right and who's wrong. It's amazing, they all use the exact same rhetoric and mimics, and I'm left wondering: What's the point?

It's time for these influential figures to take a stand and rally their followers for one crucial cause: ending the conflict. We need to unite in demanding an end to this vicious circle, end this madness, the violence, and the terror.

I've been protesting against the occupation for years, but when I see Palestinian pages posting about an 86-year-old Israeli woman being kidnapped, followed by chants of 'Free Palestine,' it's heartbreaking. My hope for humanity dies.

Let's get straight to the point‚Äîthere's only one message we should be spreading right now: PEACE. We must STOP this war, NOW.

üí¨ Leviathan: Symbolises a strong, overarching government that upholds law & order, protects lives & property. Hobbes believed a Leviathan was needed to prevent the inevitable conflicts & violence that would result from absence of a strong governing authority.

Leviathan presents a comprehensive account of human nature, politics, & society with a¬†goal¬†to investigate the foundations of political authority & to demonstrate the need for a strong, centralised state. Introduces concept of social contract, where individuals surrender¬†some of their natural rights in exchange for security & protection from a sovereign authority. Key text in history of political thought bcs it establishes the foundation for modern political philosophy & concerns on role of the state.

Note that it¬†was first published in 1651 during English Civil War, a time of England's¬†great political & social upheaval‚Äîgov structure & monarchy-Parliament relations were greatly affected by the war. It has had an impact on the evolution of modern political thought, as well as the concepts of sovereignty, the social contract, & individual rights. Hobbes' ideas about the need for a strong central authority to maintain order & security are still debated in today's discussions about governance & the balance of state power & individual liberties. The exploration of human nature & potential for conflict discussed signifies understanding international relations & conflicts dynamics.

Reading this reminds me of Das Capital as social ownership & property is a complex issue influenced by many philosophical traditions. Hobbes envisions a strong, centralised state that maintains order & security, while Marxism envisions a classless society from capitalism. Leviathan aims to¬†prevents chaos & violence, whilst¬†Marxism views the state as a tool of class oppression that protects the ruling class & enforces private property rights. Both theories emphasise the need for a strong state to prevent conflict & maintain stability, but Marxism envisions a society without a controlling¬†state.

Overall, recommended for those who‚Äôd like to understand political philosophy & governance. Swipe left to see my notes on Islmic POV.

"The Tale of Zatoichi" is a classic that started a series of films that lasted from 1962 to 1973; 25 films in total. Then in 1974, a television series was created about Zatoichi which starred the same lead actor, Shintaro Katsu, and it lasted for 100 episodes. There was one final film of Zatoichi in 1989 that was written and directed by Katsu. There was even an American remake of "Zatoichi Challenged" (the 17th film of the Zatoichi series) and it was titled "Blind Fury" (it starred the late Rutger Hauer). There have been several reimaginings of Zatoichi (including one directed by and starring Takeshi Kitano) and there will probably be more in the future.
Enough talk about the history lesson, let's talk about the first film in this long running series.

"The Tale of Zatoichi" is about a blind swordsman named Ichi who is hired by an yakuza gang since they believe a war is inevitable with the rival gang. Ichi becomes close friends with a fellow talented swordsman, Hirate. Unfortunately, Ichi and Hirate know they will most likely have to duel each other since Hirate is hired by the rival gang.

What makes this film so great is that it focuses on character drama and conflict for majority of its runtime. You get to know these characters rather well and it makes the one big action scene at the end have so much more of an impact on the viewer. The cinematography of this film is drop dead gorgeous. Cinematographer Chishi Makiura knows how to use deep focus and low key lighting for some harsh shadows in order to capture the tension of the personal conflicts of these characters. Shintaro Katsu brings such charisma and likability to the tragic character of Ichi that you will understand why Japanese audiences were obsessed with this character for decades.

I highly recommend watching this film. The only complaint I have with it is that the first 20 minutes are rather slow.

Those who have ambitions of glory, who can and will make history, know that history is a game. For the others, who are their pawns, history is a succession of catastrophes: history is the controversy for which they are the gags, the dispute for which they are the plugs, the war for which they are the corpses, the embrace for which they are the prohibition. The players that recognize this extreme game that goes beyond their life know that they must actually go beyond themselves; and this may not be enough. Far from discouraging them, this immeasurable necessity attracts them. I will not enumerate the qualities that are necessary in order to win, because everything is useful. I only want to show that the aim is the victory, that history is short!

The enemies of history affirm: that history is long; and also: that history is determined. Thus, this absolute game is the game for the (pre)dominance of the totality, which belongs to all humanity, but also the conflict of divided humanity. In fact, what makes this game absolute is that it has no rules other than those established by the participants and so always completely ephemeral. The sacred is a rule of the profane game; the infinite is the labyrinth of illusion in history. The absolute is itself only a rule implied in establishing explicit rules.

Finally, history is to life what the daily reality is to survival, the measure of its time. The game is the general activity of the human being, where intelligence is the unity of heart and mind. In his need to practice the game, history, the human being encounters necessity as misery, as accident, as the alienation of his intelligence. Our epoch completes the world showing work opposed to the game, necessity opposed to life, daily reality opposed to richness.

-Adreba Solneman, as But Which History Is This?

Rational choice theory is a foundational framework in the field of international relations that seeks to explain the decision-making processes of states and actors in the international system. This theory assumes that these actors are rational, self-interested, and driven by a desire to maximize their utility or well-being. In essence, they carefully weigh the costs and benefits of different courses of action and select the one that promises the highest net gain. This perspective has broad applications in international relations, including alliance formation, nuclear weapons acquisition, trade policy, and conflict resolution.
While rational choice theory provides valuable insights into state behavior, it has faced criticism for oversimplifying human decision-making by overlooking emotional and cultural factors. Nonetheless, it remains a useful tool for understanding the pursuit of national interests and strategic decision-making in international politics. It's important to note that in practice, real-world decision-making is often influenced by a mix of rational calculations, external constraints, and non-rational elements, making international relations a complex and multifaceted field of study.
Rational choice theory is applied to explain how states and actors make decisions based on self-interest and utility maximization. Examples include alliance formation for security, nuclear proliferation for deterrence, trade policy for economic benefits, and crisis decision-making. It also helps analyze choices related to international organizations, economic sanctions, conflict resolution, and international treaties. While the theory emphasizes rational calculations, it acknowledges that decision-making can be influenced by various factors, including non-rational elements and external constraints. #rationalchoice #internationalrelations #internationalrelationstheory #rational #tradepolicy #talkdiplomacy #upsc #css #upscmotivation #csstricks #upscaspirants #decisionmaking #multifacated #internationalpolitics #geopolitics #nuclearproliferation #internationalrelationsstudent #economicbenefits #decisionmaking #constraints #economicsanctions #unitednations #warandpeace

New Delhi: On Friday, October 6, a two-judge bench of the Supreme Court comprising Justices Vikram Nath and Rajesh Bindal, in Joginder Pal vs The State of Himachal Pradesh,  stayed the Himachal Pradesh high court‚Äôs order dated April 26, 2023, setting aside the findings of the court below that the accused be treated as major and be tried accordingly. The high court had also ordered an ossification test of the accused to be conducted by the Juvenile Justice Board, and depending upon the report of the Testing Authority, dealing with the accused in accordance with law.

In the instant case, the Juvenile Justice Board (JJB) held the murder-accused in a road rage case to be a juvenile on September 19, 2014, finding his age below 18 years of age on the date of the incident, June 20, 2014. The father of the deceased challenged the JJB‚Äôs order before the Court of Sessions Judge, Mandi (Himachal Pradesh) which allowed the appeal, setting aside JJB‚Äôs order with a direction to make an inquiry for determination of the age of the accused and thereafter to proceed with the matter in accordance with the law.

Thereafter, another order was passed by the JJB on May 26, 2017, again finding the age of the accused to be below 18 years, and he was declared as juvenile in conflict with law. The father of the deceased again assailed the order by way of an appeal, and in terms of judgment dated February 28, 2018, the appellate court set aside the JJB‚Äôs order, and issued directions to make a fresh inquiry for determination of the age of the accused and to proceed with the matter thereafter.

The accused, Shiv Kumar alias Shivam, filed a criminal revision petition before the high court, alleging that he was not heard by the appellate court before passing the order on February 28, 2018. The high court set aside the order of the appellate court, directing it to hear the matter afresh after hearing the accused. Upon remand, the appellate court again set aside the JJB‚Äôs order dated May 26, 2017, and directed the Board to make an inquiry for determination of the age of the accused.

In this standalone addition to The Alpha Elite Series, we meet Delta, a Navy SEAL turned private security expert. Known for his foresight and precision, Delta navigates the world with an unmatched ability to predict and strategize. UAE President holds phone calls with heads of state of Jordan, Egypt, Syria, Israel, and Canada to discuss regional developments

President His Highness Sheikh Mohamed bin Zayed Al 
Nahyan today spoke by telephone to a number of leaders and heads of state to discuss the latest regional developments.

In separate phone calls, His Highness spoke to His Majesty King Abdullah II bin Al Hussein of the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan; Abdel Fattah El Sisi, President of the Arab Republic of Egypt; Bashar Al-Assad, President of the Syrian Arab Republic; Isaac Herzog, President of the State of Israel; and Justin Trudeau, Prime Minister of Canada.

During the discussions, His Highness Sheikh Mohamed emphasised the urgent need for de-escalation and called on all sides to exercise restraint in order to safeguard the lives of civilians. The UAE President reiterated the importance of dialogue and diplomacy, and encouraged the international community to support all efforts aimed at avoiding further conflict that jeopardises the security and stability of the region and its people.

MEDIA STATEMENT ON RECENT EVENTS IN GAZA
8 OCTOBER 2023
